New
Andrena species
from Central Asia ( Hymenoptera , Andrenidae )

The bee genus 

Andrena

is the second most speciose globally, with almost 1,700 species following recent revisions (GUSENLEITNER & SCHWARZ 2002; ASCHER & PICKERING 2020; 

; 
WOOD
& MONFARED 2022; 

; 

). It is known for its taxonomic complexity (

), in part due to its rapid speciation rate (

) which means that 

Andrena

lineages often do not accumulate distinctive morphological differences, even if they can be well-separated genetically and behaviourally (e.g. 

).

Andrena
shows the highest species richness in areas with Mediterranean to xeric climates, and consequently have very high species richness in countries such as Turkey , Spain , Israel , and Iran (
; WOOD & MONFARED 2022;
;
). It might therefore be expected that Central Asia, a vast area of dry deserts, steppe, and mountains, would also host a rich
Andrena
fauna. However, as defined as comprising Kazakhstan , Turkmenistan , Uzbekistan , Tajikistan , and Kyrgyzstan , Central Asia surprisingly has a relatively mediocre
Andrena
fauna, with around 230 species considered present in the published literature (e.g.
;
; ASCHER & PICKERING 2020). For comparison, this is only slightly more than the 228 species known from the Iberian Peninsula (
), and marginally more than the 197 species known from neighbouring Iran ( WOOD & MONFARED 2022). For individual countries, the results are even more mediocre ‚Äì for example, only 43
Andrena species
are listed from Kyrgyzstan (
; ASCHER & PICKERING 2020), reflecting its lack of study. Only three
Andrena species
have been described from Kyrgyzstan (
;
;
), with essentially no historical taxonomic work compared to other Central Asian countries (e.g.
;
;
;
;
).

Recent photographic documentation of important 
type
material for 

Andrena
species

described from Central Asia by Ferdinand MORAWITZ (

; 

) combined with the partially published monograph of Anna OSYTSHNJUK (

; 

) has facilitated a renewed study of Central Asian 

Andrena

and their relationship with 

Andrena

taxa in other biogeographic regions (
WOOD
& MONFARED 2022; 

). The current work continues to build on these previous contributions with the description of four new species from this understudied part of the world.

